32 27 Sic mihi persuasi: four proofs of the immortality of the soul follow: (1) its great capacity; (2) its innate power of motion; (3) its homogeneity of substance ; (4) its pre-existence.

See note on 1, p. 1, l. 11.—tantae scientiae: scientia means not ‘scienee‚’ but ‘knowledge,’ and can no more properly be used in the plural than can that English word. It is found in classical Latin only here (see Moore ad loc.) and must be translated ‘branches of knowledge’ or ‘range of knowledge!
